<p>That changed bumped our scenario down one line. Put the new line into the terminal
and run it:</p>
<pre><code class="language-bash"><div class="line">./vendor/bin/behat features/product_admin.feature:20</div></code></pre>
<p>Just make sure that the Selenium server is still running in the background. Watch
closely. Well, don't watch that silly Firefox error. We log in, go to the products
page, clicks the "New Product" button, fill in the form fields, and hit "Save". It's
perfect.</p>
<h2 id="waiting-for-things-to-happen">Waiting for things to Happen <a class="headerlink" href="javascript-waiting#waiting-for-things-to-happen" title="Permalink to this headline"><i class="fa fa-link" aria-hidden="true"></i></a></h2>
<p>Reality check: if I re-ran this 5 times, I bet it would fail at least once. Let me
show you why. In <code>ProductAdminController</code> pretend this isn't such a fast ajax request.
Add a <code>sleep(1)</code> to fake the time it would take to do some logic.</p>
<p>Re-run things:</p>
<pre><code class="language-bash"><div class="line">./vendor/bin/behat features/product_admin.feature:20</div></code></pre>
<p>We log in, click the button... and the browser closes! We didn't see it fill out
any fields. In the terminal, it failed at:</p>
<p><div class="code-block-wrapper" data-code-block-guid="b429c2f663">
    <div class="meta">
        <div class="actions">
            <span class="fa fa-clipboard js-activate-clipboard" data-toggle="tooltip" title="Copy Code" data-placement="top"></span>
        </div>
